{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568404"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:15:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:15:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20503"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20503"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.03,0.11,0.57,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13376"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92655"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13376"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20503"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75997"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"2967"},{"type":"tags","id":"3460"},{"type":"tags","id":"4208"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"6442"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31751"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31753"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43951"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92655"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of increased urinary frequency and mild dysuria. She has no abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, fever, or jaundice. She has a medical history of hypertension and migraine. Her medications include amlodipine and sumatriptan as needed. She works as an accountant and does not smoke or drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender with no palpable masses or organomegaly. Urinalysis shows trace leukocytes but is negative for nitrites. An abdominal ultrasound is ordered to investigate her urinary symptoms, which shows normal kidneys and bladder. The right kidney shows a 2.5 cm simple cyst, consistent with a Bosniak I lesion. Incidentally, the gallbladder contains three gallstones measuring 5-8 mm without wall thickening or pericholecystic fluid. The liver, pancreas, and biliary tree appear normal with no biliary dilatation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management for the gallstones?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ursodeoxycholic acid therapy","Extracorporeal shock wave lithotripsy","Laparoscopic cholecystectomy","Observation without specific intervention","Low-fat diet and regular follow-up ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has incidentally discovered gallstones on ultrasound performed for urinary symptoms. The absence of any symptoms of biliary disease, normal gallbladder wall, and absence of biliary dilatation indicate asymptomatic cholelithiasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn western communities, it is estimated that some 30% of individuals will develop gallstones over their lifetime. For most people their presence will remain unknown, but each year some 2 - 4% of these individuals will develop symptoms. Biliary colic is the most common symptom. The natural history of asymptomatic gallstones is generally benign, with only about 20% of patients developing symptoms over 20 years. The risk of complications (such as acute cholecystitis, pancreatitis, or cholangitis) is even lower at approximately 1-2% per year.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation without specific intervention\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management for asymptomatic gallstones. The natural history of asymptomatic gallstones is generally benign, with only 2-4% of patients developing symptoms or complications per year. Most patients with asymptomatic gallstones will never develop symptoms related to their gallstones. Given the low risk of developing complications, routine intervention is not justified.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic cholecystectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the definitive treatment for symptomatic gallstone disease but is not indicated for asymptomatic gallstones in most patients. Surgery carries risks including bile duct injury, bleeding, and anaesthetic complications. Prophylactic cholecystectomy may be considered in select populations (e.g., patients with sickle cell disease, planned bariatric surgery, or gallbladder polyps), but this patient does not fall into any of these categories.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrsodeoxycholic acid therapy\u003C/strong\u003E can dissolve cholesterol gallstones in some patients but has limited efficacy, requires prolonged treatment (6-24 months), and has a high recurrence rate after discontinuation. It is occasionally used in patients who refuse or are unfit for surgery but is not indicated for asymptomatic gallstones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow-fat diet and regular follow-up ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is not evidence-based management for asymptomatic gallstones. Dietary modifications have not been shown to prevent complications in patients with asymptomatic gallstones, and routine surveillance imaging is unnecessary in the absence of symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtracorporeal shock wave lithotripsy\u003C/strong\u003E is rarely used for gallstone management in current practice. It has limited efficacy, high recurrence rates, and is only suitable for solitary, radiolucent stones. It is not indicated for asymptomatic gallstones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient should be educated about symptoms of biliary colic or complications (e.g., right upper quadrant pain, especially after fatty meals, associated with nausea/vomiting) that would warrant reassessment. The renal cyst is an incidental finding and should be monitored according to guidelines for Bosniak I lesions, which typically require no specific intervention. The patient\u0027s urinary symptoms should be addressed separately, likely representing a urinary tract infection requiring appropriate antibiotic therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Asymptomatic cholelithiasis discovered incidentally does not require intervention in most patients.","The natural history of asymptomatic gallstones is benign, with only 2-4% of patients developing symptoms annually.","Prophylactic cholecystectomy for asymptomatic gallstones is not recommended due to the low risk of complications and the risks associated with surgery."],"references":["Patel H, Jepsen J. Gallstone Disease: Common Questions and Answers. Am Fam Physician. 2024;109(6):518-524"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75997"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20503"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75997"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-18T18:38:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T14:51:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13376"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92655"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastro